hands_on_practices.solution:
We are given the Pauli matrices
$$
\sigma_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 \\[4pt] 1 & 0\end{pmatrix},\quad
\sigma_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & -i \\[4pt] i & 0\end{pmatrix},\quad
\sigma_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\[4pt] 0 & -1\end{pmatrix},
$$
and the commutator definition $[A,B]=AB-BA$. We compute $[\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2}]$ explicitly by first evaluating the products $\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}$ and $\sigma_{2}\sigma_{1}$ using standard matrix multiplication.

Compute $\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}$:
$$
\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}
= \begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 \\[4pt] 1 & 0\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}0 & -i \\[4pt] i & 0\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}0 \cdot 0 + 1 \cdot i & 0 \cdot (-i) + 1 \cdot 0 \\[4pt] 1 \cdot 0 + 0 \cdot i & 1 \cdot (-i) + 0 \cdot 0\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}i & 0 \\[4pt] 0 & -i\end{pmatrix}
= i\,\sigma_{3}.
$$

Compute $\sigma_{2}\sigma_{1}$:
$$
\sigma_{2}\sigma_{1}
= \begin{pmatrix}0 & -i \\[4pt] i & 0\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 \\[4pt] 1 & 0\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}0 \cdot 0 + (-i) \cdot 1 & 0 \cdot 1 + (-i) \cdot 0 \\[4pt] i \cdot 0 + 0 \cdot 1 & i \cdot 1 + 0 \cdot 0\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}-i & 0 \\[4pt] 0 & i\end{pmatrix}
= -i\,\sigma_{3}.
$$

Now apply the commutator definition:
$$
[\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2}]=\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}-\sigma_{2}\sigma_{1}
=i\,\sigma_{3}-(-i)\,\sigma_{3}
=2i\,\sigma_{3}.
$$

Thus the constant $C$ in $[\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2}]=C\,\sigma_{3}$ is $2i$, which corresponds to option D.
